There&#39;s a few things I can recommend.

 - You can combine your two loops where you `.getText()` to get the string and then convert the string to a number (with several steps) and just do both in that single loop.

 - Your cleanup of the string and parsing to a number can be simplified. You don&#39;t need to remove the &#39;$&#39; and then process it. You can instead use `NumberFormat.getCurrencyInstance()` and use the currency string directly. This removes the need for `cropAndParseToDecimal()`.

 - You are using `Locale.GERMAN` (the language) when it should be `Locale.GERMANY` (the country). Having said that, you are processing US currency &#39;$&#39; so you actually should be using `Locale.US` when parsing.

       Number n = NumberFormat.getCurrencyInstance(Locale.US).parse(&quot;$1.00&quot;)

- You don&#39;t need `BigDecimal`s here since you aren&#39;t writing a bank app, you are just scraping currency strings off the site and validating. Using `Double` here should be fine and go faster.

Rolling all these suggestions up,

    List&lt;WebElement&gt; productPricesWE = baseMethods.findElements(&quot;ProductListing.ProductPrice&quot;);
    List&lt;Double&gt; productPrices = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    for (WebElement element : productPricesWE) {
        String s = element.getText().trim().replaceAll(&quot;€* &quot;, &quot;&quot;);
        productPrices.add(NumberFormat.getNumberInstance(Locale.GERMANY).parse(s).doubleValue());
    }

    Assert.assertTrue(Ordering.natural().isOrdered(productPrices));

-----

Having said all that, my guess is that my code is probably 100ms faster than your code which is negligible on any web UI test. I like it slightly better not because it&#39;s faster but some of the functions are simpler and more straightforward.

Remember the rule, you write code once and read it ten times. Always prefer readable code over lengthy &quot;one-liners&quot; or excessively shortened code.

